adaptive daydreaming","cfs/medications","tv tropes","quiz","exit","палимпсест времени","Jan 8th, 2026","Aug 20th, 2025","Dec 12th, 2025","cfs","aug 20th, 2025","diary","May 19th, 2024"]],536879776]],["^15",[3842,"^Q","",536870924]],["^15",[3842,"^O","^17",536870924]],["^15",[3842,"^@",false,536870924]],["^15",[3842,"^F",23,536870924]],["^15",[3842,"^X",23,536870924]],["^15",[3842,"^V",23,536870924]],["^15",[3842,"^U",23,536870925]],["^15",[3842,"^?",["^ "],536870924]],["^15",[3842,"^;","~u69a84628-72fc-4699-b9cd-3300ff0e4091",536870924]],["^15",[3843,"^Q","",536870928]],["^15",[3843,"^O","^17",536870928]],["^15",[3843,"^@",false,536870928]],["^15",[3843,"^F",317,536870928]],["^15",[3843,"^X",317,536870928]],["^15",[3843,"^V",317,536870928]],["^15",[3843,"^U",317,536870929]],["^15",[3843,"^?",["^ "],536870928]],["^15",[3843,"^;","~u69a8462d-8681-4413-a371-ee91890a7704",536870928]],["^15",[3844,"^K",1772635718534,536870932]],["^15",[3844,"^[",3846,536870937]],["^15",[3844,"^O","^17",536870933]],["^15",[3844,"^N",20260301,536870932]],["^15",[3844,"^@",true,536870932]],["^15",[3844,"^Y","mar 1st, 2026",536870932]],["^15",[3844,"^11","Mar 1st, 2026",536870932]],["^15",[3844,"^B",1772635790158,536870975]],["^15",[3844,"^;","~u69a84646-ac9d-40f9-83a4-3e5a6d6ab765",536870932]],["^15",[3845,"^Q","[[linguistics/phonetics/prosody]] [[languages/Chechen language]]",536870975]],["^15",[3845,"^O","^17",536870934]],["^15",[3845,"^N",20260301,536870934]],["^15",[3845,"^@",true,536870934]],["^15",[3845,"^F",3844,536870934]],["^15",[3845,"^X",3844,536870934]],["^15",[3845,"^V",3844,536870934]],["^15",[3845,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3845,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3845,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3845,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3845,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3845,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3845,"^?",["^ "],536870975]],["^15",[3845,"^H",20,536870975]],["^15",[3845,"^H",22,536870975]],["^15",[3845,"^H",23,536870975]],["^15",[3845,"^H",317,536870975]],["^15",[3845,"^H",318,536870975]],["^15",[3845,"^;","~u69a84647-4b1f-4503-9ea9-9ff985b19cce",536870934]],["^15",[3846,"^3","- [[linguistics/phonetics/prosody]] [[languages/Chechen language]]\n\t- Ingush Grammar by J. Nichols\n\t  id:: 6935f2eb-bb67-451e-8ea5-f7e3e6554394\n\t  collapsed:: true\n\t\t- \"Ingush prosody consists of stress, usually initial but in a few instances on the second syllable; a rule of phrasal accent that parses certain phrase types, from right to left, into a two-stress or two-word minimal prosodic unit or intonational phrase (IP); a minimal tone opposition (high vs. unmarked), distinct from stress; and pitch declination over the entire clause or sentence or utterance. Stress, phrasal accent, and tone are three separate phonemic categories. Pitch and declination are phonetic notions: pitch is the absolute pitch of the fundamental frequency, and declination is its regular drop over some domain.\"\n\t\t- Stress\n\t\t\t- \"Nearly every Ingush simplex word has a tonic syllable, and\n\t\t\t  in nearly all Ingush words the tonic syllable is the initial syllable. Phonetically, stress is marked by greater prominence and the capacity to bear phrasal accent; a word pronounced in isolation has primary phrasal accent on its stressed syllable, which is therefore higher in pitch than the rest. Phonologically, stress is marked by the fact that posttonic vowel reduction turns all posttonic short vowels to schwa.\"\n\t\t\t- \"Accentable words include major class words (nouns, verbs, adjectives) and their derivatives (e.g. adverbs), as well as elements that are not lexically words: local prefixes of\n\t\t\t  verbs, all first elements of compounds no matter what their lexical status. Non-accentable words include all clitics as well as some pronouns (at least the possessive personal pronouns\n\t\t\t  and the basic demonstrative modifiers yz 'that; aforementioned' and jer 'this'). These do not bear the primary stress in NP's, while noun and adjective modifiers do.\"\n\t\t- Tone\n\t\t\t- \"Ingush has a minimal tone system which is interesting precisely for being so minimal and yet so clearly a tone system.\"\n\t\t\t- \"non-initial stress may well be the source of Chechen-Ingush high tone. At least for Ingush high tone cannot easily be analyzed as stress: Ingush has mostly fixed initial stress whose side effects are prototypically those of stress and not tone, such as reduction of unstressed vowels to schwa; some of the high-tone morphemes contain this schwa, and those that assign the actual high pitch to a preceding syllable easily assign it to a schwa. Hence Ingush has both stress (mostly fixed initial) and tone (high vs. lack of tone). Distinctive high tone appears most often on unstressed syllables. The finite verb bears a pitch contour unique to it: a sharp rise-fall located on the tonic syllable or a high-toned suffix.\"\n\t\t\t- \"lâtar 'used to fight' (imperfect)\n\t\t\t   latâr 'fought' (witnessed past) (lätar)\n\t\t\t   látar 'fighting, a fight' (verb\n\t\t\t  Impressionistically, the witnessed past sounds rather like a Bosnian/Croatian/Serbian disyllable with rising pitch (though the sharp fall to a low tone in the following word, i.e. after the high-fall tone, is unlike Bosnian/Croatian/Serbian). The verbal noun sounds like an initial-stressed word in any stress language, or like a word with a falling tone in Bosnian/Croatian/Serbian. The imperfect, with its sharp rise\n\t\t\t  (clearly audible even on a short vowel) and sharp fall to a low pitch on the following syllable, sounds like something one expects to find only in a language with a system of contrastive contour tones.\"\n\t\t\t- \"The contrast of rise-fall vs. ordinary high tone on the first syllables of the imperfect and verbal noun is phonemicized, given that it is part of the ordinary pronunciation of these forms in isolation.Not all speakers perceive it as pitch, however; one of my consultants perceives it as something like stress, and the rest, though they are aware of it or can be made aware of it, seem to think of it as part of the phrasal prosody and not as part of the sound system.\"\n\t\t- Declination\n\t\t\t- Declination (or downdrift) occurs between prosodic phrases within the same clause and between clauses within a sentence. Each high accent receives successively lower\n\t\t\t  pitch. Impressionistically, phrase-to-phrase declination is about a full step or a minor third. Clause-to-clause declination is optional; various kinds of pauses and emphases can effect a reset. In the following examples, /'/ before a phrase boundary marks declination and brackets\n\t\t\t  delimit IP's.\n\t\t\t  (50) sy doáqqa ' [IP qó zhw\\alii]\n\t\t\t   1s.GEN D.big three dog\n\t\t\t   'my three big dogs'\n\t\t\t  (51) dieztq'îi=ji ' [IP qó zhw\\alii] {d.ieztq'a=ˆji}\n\t\t\t   D.80 & three dog\n\t\t\t   '83 dogs'\n\t\t\t  (52) [ díka s\\ag ] ' [IP v»y M\\uusaa]\n\t\t\t   good person V.be.RS Musa\n\t\t\t   'Musa is a good person'\n\t\t- \"There is no simple notion of prosodic wordhood in Ingush. The simplex word (major class root ± suffixes) is the domain of tonic stress assignment. The compound or prosodic two-stress phrase is the domain of primary and secondary stress assignment, and can be anything from a true morphological compound to a free syntactic phrase or even (since parsing for primary and secondary stress assignment begins at the right of the phrase) a nonconstituent comprising the last two tonic words of a phrase.\"\n\t- Если в руссокм языке ударение резко поднимается на ударном слоге и плавно опускается, то в чеченском, вроде, наоборот: плавно поднимается, задерживается на пике и опускается сравнительно быстро.",536870978]],["^15",[3846,"^18","~m1772635790828",536870977]],["^15",[3846,"^Z","journals/2026_03_01.md",536870937]],["^15",[3847,"^M",true,536870953]],["^15",[3847,"^Q","Ingush Grammar by J. Nichols\nid:: 6935f2eb-bb67-451e-8ea5-f7e3e6554394\ncollapsed:: true",536870953]],["^15",[3847,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3847,"^F",3845,536870953]],["^15",[3847,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3847,"^V",3845,536870959]],["^15",[3847,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3847,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3847,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3847,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3847,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3847,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3847,"^?",["^ ","^1>","6935f2eb-bb67-451e-8ea5-f7e3e6554394"],536870953]],["^15",[3847,"^J",["^14",["^1>"]],536870953]],["^15",[3847,"^4",["^ ","^1>","6935f2eb-bb67-451e-8ea5-f7e3e6554394"],536870953]],["^15",[3847,"^;","~u6935f2eb-bb67-451e-8ea5-f7e3e6554394",536870953]],["^15",[3848,"^Q","\"Ingush prosody consists of stress, usually initial but in a few instances on the second syllable; a rule of phrasal accent that parses certain phrase types, from right to left, into a two-stress or two-word minimal prosodic unit or intonational phrase (IP); a minimal tone opposition (high vs. unmarked), distinct from stress; and pitch declination over the entire clause or sentence or utterance. Stress, phrasal accent, and tone are three separate phonemic categories. Pitch and declination are phonetic notions: pitch is the absolute pitch of the fundamental frequency, and declination is its regular drop over some domain.\"",536870953]],["^15",[3848,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3848,"^F",3847,536870953]],["^15",[3848,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3848,"^V",3847,536870953]],["^15",[3848,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3848,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3848,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3848,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3848,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3848,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3848,"^;","~u69a845e8-0307-46d1-86f6-cdfb37ef4cff",536870953]],["^15",[3849,"^Q","Stress",536870953]],["^15",[3849,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3849,"^F",3848,536870953]],["^15",[3849,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3849,"^V",3847,536870953]],["^15",[3849,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3849,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3849,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3849,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3849,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3849,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3849,"^;","~u69a845e8-b613-4355-b162-182cdf64aef0",536870953]],["^15",[3850,"^Q","\"Nearly every Ingush simplex word has a tonic syllable, and\nin nearly all Ingush words the tonic syllable is the initial syllable. Phonetically, stress is marked by greater prominence and the capacity to bear phrasal accent; a word pronounced in isolation has primary phrasal accent on its stressed syllable, which is therefore higher in pitch than the rest. Phonologically, stress is marked by the fact that posttonic vowel reduction turns all posttonic short vowels to schwa.\"",536870953]],["^15",[3850,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3850,"^F",3849,536870953]],["^15",[3850,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3850,"^V",3849,536870953]],["^15",[3850,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3850,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3850,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3850,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3850,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3850,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3850,"^;","~u69a845e8-ca6e-485c-80df-5ffd17ee8b25",536870953]],["^15",[3851,"^Q","\"Accentable words include major class words (nouns, verbs, adjectives) and their derivatives (e.g. adverbs), as well as elements that are not lexically words: local prefixes of\nverbs, all first elements of compounds no matter what their lexical status. Non-accentable words include all clitics as well as some pronouns (at least the possessive personal pronouns\nand the basic demonstrative modifiers yz 'that; aforementioned' and jer 'this'). These do not bear the primary stress in NP's, while noun and adjective modifiers do.\"",536870953]],["^15",[3851,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3851,"^F",3850,536870953]],["^15",[3851,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3851,"^V",3849,536870953]],["^15",[3851,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3851,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3851,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3851,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3851,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3851,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3851,"^;","~u69a845e8-ad3b-4d73-bcaa-a9132545bd31",536870953]],["^15",[3852,"^Q","Tone",536870953]],["^15",[3852,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3852,"^F",3849,536870953]],["^15",[3852,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3852,"^V",3847,536870953]],["^15",[3852,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3852,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3852,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3852,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3852,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3852,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3852,"^;","~u69a845e8-4e7d-40b0-87ff-89f744b8c4f6",536870953]],["^15",[3853,"^Q","\"Ingush has a minimal tone system which is interesting precisely for being so minimal and yet so clearly a tone system.\"",536870953]],["^15",[3853,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3853,"^F",3852,536870953]],["^15",[3853,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3853,"^V",3852,536870953]],["^15",[3853,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3853,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3853,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3853,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3853,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3853,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3853,"^;","~u69a845e7-f79f-4e89-94e1-1edfd7c351d2",536870953]],["^15",[3854,"^Q","\"non-initial stress may well be the source of Chechen-Ingush high tone. At least for Ingush high tone cannot easily be analyzed as stress: Ingush has mostly fixed initial stress whose side effects are prototypically those of stress and not tone, such as reduction of unstressed vowels to schwa; some of the high-tone morphemes contain this schwa, and those that assign the actual high pitch to a preceding syllable easily assign it to a schwa. Hence Ingush has both stress (mostly fixed initial) and tone (high vs. lack of tone). Distinctive high tone appears most often on unstressed syllables. The finite verb bears a pitch contour unique to it: a sharp rise-fall located on the tonic syllable or a high-toned suffix.\"",536870953]],["^15",[3854,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3854,"^F",3853,536870953]],["^15",[3854,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3854,"^V",3852,536870953]],["^15",[3854,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3854,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3854,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3854,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3854,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3854,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3854,"^;","~u69a845e7-c078-4987-bf2d-54e0246b2be7",536870953]],["^15",[3855,"^Q","\"lâtar 'used to fight' (imperfect)\n latâr 'fought' (witnessed past) (lätar)\n látar 'fighting, a fight' (verb\nImpressionistically, the witnessed past sounds rather like a Bosnian/Croatian/Serbian disyllable with rising pitch (though the sharp fall to a low tone in the following word, i.e. after the high-fall tone, is unlike Bosnian/Croatian/Serbian). The verbal noun sounds like an initial-stressed word in any stress language, or like a word with a falling tone in Bosnian/Croatian/Serbian. The imperfect, with its sharp rise\n(clearly audible even on a short vowel) and sharp fall to a low pitch on the following syllable, sounds like something one expects to find only in a language with a system of contrastive contour tones.\"",536870953]],["^15",[3855,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3855,"^F",3854,536870953]],["^15",[3855,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3855,"^V",3852,536870953]],["^15",[3855,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3855,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3855,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3855,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3855,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3855,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3855,"^;","~u69a845e7-d722-42ff-9fb5-2ff33c0ecc03",536870953]],["^15",[3856,"^Q","\"The contrast of rise-fall vs. ordinary high tone on the first syllables of the imperfect and verbal noun is phonemicized, given that it is part of the ordinary pronunciation of these forms in isolation.Not all speakers perceive it as pitch, however; one of my consultants perceives it as something like stress, and the rest, though they are aware of it or can be made aware of it, seem to think of it as part of the phrasal prosody and not as part of the sound system.\"",536870953]],["^15",[3856,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3856,"^F",3855,536870953]],["^15",[3856,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3856,"^V",3852,536870953]],["^15",[3856,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3856,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3856,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3856,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3856,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3856,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3856,"^;","~u69a845e7-bd8c-4749-a7f0-723121ef6ca6",536870953]],["^15",[3857,"^Q","Declination",536870953]],["^15",[3857,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3857,"^F",3852,536870953]],["^15",[3857,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3857,"^V",3847,536870953]],["^15",[3857,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3857,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3857,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3857,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3857,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3857,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3857,"^;","~u69a845e7-b9ea-4fd4-b949-63792b683ea0",536870953]],["^15",[3858,"^Q","Declination (or downdrift) occurs between prosodic phrases within the same clause and between clauses within a sentence. Each high accent receives successively lower\npitch. Impressionistically, phrase-to-phrase declination is about a full step or a minor third. Clause-to-clause declination is optional; various kinds of pauses and emphases can effect a reset. In the following examples, /'/ before a phrase boundary marks declination and brackets\ndelimit IP's.\n(50) sy doáqqa ' [IP qó zhw\\alii]\n 1s.GEN D.big three dog\n 'my three big dogs'\n(51) dieztq'îi=ji ' [IP qó zhw\\alii] {d.ieztq'a=ˆji}\n D.80 & three dog\n '83 dogs'\n(52) [ díka s\\ag ] ' [IP v»y M\\uusaa]\n good person V.be.RS Musa\n 'Musa is a good person'",536870953]],["^15",[3858,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3858,"^F",3857,536870953]],["^15",[3858,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3858,"^V",3857,536870953]],["^15",[3858,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3858,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3858,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3858,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3858,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3858,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3858,"^;","~u69a845e7-df3b-44df-a63c-5fc249e178e8",536870953]],["^15",[3859,"^Q","\"There is no simple notion of prosodic wordhood in Ingush. The simplex word (major class root ± suffixes) is the domain of tonic stress assignment. The compound or prosodic two-stress phrase is the domain of primary and secondary stress assignment, and can be anything from a true morphological compound to a free syntactic phrase or even (since parsing for primary and secondary stress assignment begins at the right of the phrase) a nonconstituent comprising the last two tonic words of a phrase.\"",536870953]],["^15",[3859,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3859,"^F",3857,536870953]],["^15",[3859,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3859,"^V",3847,536870953]],["^15",[3859,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3859,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3859,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3859,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3859,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3859,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3859,"^;","~u69a845e7-39ca-40f9-a22e-c3798e81509e",536870953]],["^15",[3860,"^Q","Если в руссокм языке ударение резко поднимается на ударном слоге и плавно опускается, то в чеченском, вроде, наоборот: плавно поднимается, задерживается на пике и опускается сравнительно быстро.",536870953]],["^15",[3860,"^O","^17",536870953]],["^15",[3860,"^F",3847,536870953]],["^15",[3860,"^X",3844,536870953]],["^15",[3860,"^V",3845,536870959]],["^15",[3860,"^U",20,536870976]],["^15",[3860,"^U",22,536870976]],["^15",[3860,"^U",23,536870976]],["^15",[3860,"^U",317,536870976]],["^15",[3860,"^U",318,536870976]],["^15",[3860,"^U",3844,536870976]],["^15",[3860,"^;","~u69a845e7-8372-4492-a924-88859dfb36e2",536870953]],["^15",[3861,"^K",1772635845840,536870987]],["^15",[3861,"^[",3864,536871009]],["^15",[3861,"^O","^17",536870988]],["^15",[3861,"^N",20260228,536870987]],["^15",[3861,"^@",true,536870987]],["^15",[3861,"^Y","feb 28th, 2026",536870987]],["^15",[3861,"^11","Feb 28th, 2026",536870987]],["^15",[3861,"^B",1772635962720,536871046]],["^15",[3861,"^;","~u69a846c5-aa31-4a31-8fe6-7cd8838ae324",536870987]],["^15",[3862,"^Q","[[linguistics/grammar]] [[languages/English language]]",536871013]],["^15",[3862,"^O","^17",536870989]],["^15",[3862,"^N",20260228,536870989]],["^15",[3862,"^@",true,536870989]],["^15",[3862,"^F",3861,536870989]],["^15",[3862,"^X",3861,536870989]],["^15",[3862,"^V",3861,536870989]],["^15",[3862,"^U",21,536871014]],["^15",[3862,"^U",22,536871014]],["^15",[3862,"^U",23,536871014]],["^15",[3862,"^U",3162,536871014]],["^15",[3862,"^U",3861,536871014]],["^15",[3862,"^?",["^ "],536871013]],["^15",[3862,"^H",21,536871013]],["^15",[3862,"^H",22,536871013]],["^15",[3862,"^H",23,536871013]],["^15",[3862,"^H",3162,536871013]],["^15",[3862,"^;","~u69a846c8-07fe-4014-81f0-de9d34064a66",536870989]],["^15",[3863,"^Q","",536871003]],["^15",[3863,"^O","^17",536871003]],["^15",[3863,"^@",false,536871003]],["^15",[3863,"^F",21,536871003]],["^15",[3863,"^X",21,536871003]],["^15",[3863,"^V",21,536871003]],["^15",[3863,"^U",21,536871004]],["^15",[3863,"^?",["^ "],536871003]],["^15",[3863,"^;","~u69a8470d-64ce-43b3-a43e-c39d62fa1390",536871003]],["^15",[3864,"^3","- [[linguistics/grammar]] [[languages/English language]]\n\t- Относительно редкие и интересные черты английского языка\n\t\t- Dummy It” and “Dummy There” Subjects\n\t\t- True absolute constuction\n\t\t\t- Features\n\t\t\t\t- no subordinator\n\t\t\t\t- no morphological case\n\t\t\t\t- no clause-linking morpheme\n\t\t\t\t- purely positional and semantic attachment\n\t\t\t- Uses\n\t\t\t\t- being (progressive/continuous)\n\t\t\t\t- having done (perfect)\n\t\t\t\t- past participle (state/passive)\n\t\t\t\t- sometimes noun + adjective (reduced copula)",536871049]],["^15",[3864,"^18","~m1772635963682",536871048]],["^15",[3864,"^Z","journals/2026_02_28.md",536871009]],["^15",[3865,"^Q","Относительно редкие и интересные черты английского языка",536871046]],["^15",[3865,"^O","^17",536871018]],["^15",[3865,"^@",true,536871018]],["^15",[3865,"^F",3862,536871018]],["^15",[3865,"^X",3861,536871018]],["^15",[3865,"^V",3862,536871022]],["^15",[3865,"^U",21,536871031]],["^15",[3865,"^U",22,536871031]],["^15",[3865,